To compile, run the following commands:

$ make
$ su
$ make install

Note that the installation will currently create symbolic links to the project
tree instead of copying any real files.  Do not change the locations of these
links as the program will not work (it's currently hard-coded with these paths
in certain places).  Symbolic links are used to ease development and testing.
The following symbolic links are created:

/usr/lib/libIsoRealms.so
/usr/share/IsoRealms

There is currently no automated uninstall.  To uninstall, simply remove these
symbolic links.  To run the program, run from the root director of the project
tree:

$ ./IsoRealms

When first run, the program will create a symbol link at the following
location:

$HOME/.isorealms

This symbolic link points to the "default_setup" folder of the project tree.


NOTES ON USING THE PROGRAM:

The project currently contains many many memory leaks, bugs and unimplemented
features.  It *will* crash if you try to do certain things.  Run the program at
your own risk!

On starting the program, you will see the "Attract" mode.  Pressing any key
will start the menu driven "Front-End".  The only working options are:

 - Create New Map
 - Quit

Selecting "Create New Map" will invoke the Iso-Realms editor tool.  Please
note that dialogues / prompts have not yet been created for the menu actions:
"Open...", "Save" and "Save As".  Selecting these actions will currently
always assume a map name of "Test.isorealms"!

Movement in the editor is performed using the arrow keys and page-up/down.

Arrow Up    = Move North
Arrow Right = Move East
Arrow Down  = Move South
Arrow Left  = Move West
Page Up     = Move Up
Page Down   = Move Down
Escape      = Go into map editing mode (to create new zones)
Return      = Go into zone editing mode (to insert elements into a zone)
Space       = Insert Selected Element (zone editing mode)
                          or New Zone (map editing mode)
Delete      = Insert Subtraction (when block is selected)

Note that the means for inserting each element is unique to that element, e.g.
blocks require you to press space twice; once for the start point and again for
the end point, whereas jewels are inserted via a single press of space.

Keys cannot currently be configured.
